1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,815
If you're an avid computer user,

2
00:00:01,815 --> 00:00:07,395
you've most probably already encountered flat files through.txt and.csv files.

3
00:00:07,395 --> 00:00:11,250
Flat files are simple data files that have a uniform format.

4
00:00:11,250 --> 00:00:14,130
There are a number of different types of files that fall

5
00:00:14,130 --> 00:00:17,100
under the flat files category including text files,

6
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:19,890
comma separated values or.csv files,

7
00:00:19,890 --> 00:00:23,130
and tab-separated values or.tsv files.

8
00:00:23,130 --> 00:00:26,655
All of these types of files typically have a few things in common.

9
00:00:26,655 --> 00:00:29,640
They are tabular data in plain text.

10
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:32,610
Each line is a single date record.

11
00:00:32,610 --> 00:00:37,495
Each record has one or more values or fields.

12
00:00:37,495 --> 00:00:41,330
These values or fields are separated by delimiters or

13
00:00:41,330 --> 00:00:45,905
some character like tab spaces, comments, or semi-colons.

14
00:00:45,905 --> 00:00:49,295
Let's look at an example flat file from Rotten Tomatoes.

15
00:00:49,295 --> 00:00:53,525
Rotten Tomatoes is a popular website that provides reviews for movies and television.

16
00:00:53,525 --> 00:00:56,495
They also provide rankings and additional metrics from critics,

17
00:00:56,495 --> 00:01:00,070
such as the score that a critic attributed to a movie or a show.

18
00:01:00,070 --> 00:01:04,055
Unfortunately, Rotten Tomatoes isn't providing a file to download,

19
00:01:04,055 --> 00:01:06,680
so we're going to give it to you for this part of the lesson.

20
00:01:06,680 --> 00:01:08,605
Now let's take a look at the data.

21
00:01:08,605 --> 00:01:11,735
On the screen, you can see a small preview of our data.

22
00:01:11,735 --> 00:01:17,030
We've pre-gathered the Rotten Tomatoes dataset on the top 100 movies with four columns.

23
00:01:17,030 --> 00:01:18,860
The ranking of the movie,

24
00:01:18,860 --> 00:01:21,425
the critic score attributed to the film,

25
00:01:21,425 --> 00:01:22,850
the title of the movie,

26
00:01:22,850 --> 00:01:24,920
and the number of critic ratings.

27
00:01:24,920 --> 00:01:28,850
This dataset has 101 data records or rows,

28
00:01:28,850 --> 00:01:30,560
each on a different line,

29
00:01:30,560 --> 00:01:33,395
but I'm only showing you the first 11 rows here.

30
00:01:33,395 --> 00:01:35,540
Why 11 and not 10?

31
00:01:35,540 --> 00:01:40,010
Well, the first row is for the headers and the rest are the data records.

32
00:01:40,010 --> 00:01:42,545
This file is a tsv file,

33
00:01:42,545 --> 00:01:45,065
which stands for tab separated values,

34
00:01:45,065 --> 00:01:49,940
meaning that it uses spaces to separate the different values within a single data record.

35
00:01:49,940 --> 00:01:53,990
Take a brief look at how two different flat files look in a text editor.

36
00:01:53,990 --> 00:01:57,605
On the left, we have the tsv file with the tab-separated values.

37
00:01:57,605 --> 00:02:01,460
On the right, we've got the comma separated values or the csv file.

38
00:02:01,460 --> 00:02:03,140
Again, with this file,

39
00:02:03,140 --> 00:02:04,610
the first row represents

40
00:02:04,610 --> 00:02:08,555
the header variable names and the subsequent lines are the data records,

41
00:02:08,555 --> 00:02:10,925
with each line being one data record.

42
00:02:10,925 --> 00:02:16,225
The data values within a record are delimited by tabs spaces or commas.

43
00:02:16,225 --> 00:02:19,670
We know that.txt files can be a type of flat file,

44
00:02:19,670 --> 00:02:24,130
for example they can contain data with a tabular structure and with delimiters.

45
00:02:24,130 --> 00:02:26,490
The file to the left, for example,

46
00:02:26,490 --> 00:02:28,625
looks very similar to a csv file,

47
00:02:28,625 --> 00:02:30,260
but with the semicolon delimiter,

48
00:02:30,260 --> 00:02:32,405
and it's a flat.txt file.

49
00:02:32,405 --> 00:02:36,530
However,.txt files do not have to be flat files.

50
00:02:36,530 --> 00:02:38,690
Here's an example to the right where we see

51
00:02:38,690 --> 00:02:42,470
unstructured text content which is not a flat file.

52
00:02:42,470 --> 00:02:46,400
Stay with us to learn more about how to wrangle this type of unstructured data.

53
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:50,270
It's also important to note that in.xls or

54
00:02:50,270 --> 00:02:53,780
Microsoft Excel file contains much more advanced features like

55
00:02:53,780 --> 00:02:57,290
multiple sheets and different types of formatting that make it different from

56
00:02:57,290 --> 00:03:01,180
flat files that are storing data as part of a tabular structured.

57
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:02,955
Take a look at this example.

58
00:03:02,955 --> 00:03:07,040
When you open a.xlxx file in Microsoft Excel,

59
00:03:07,040 --> 00:03:09,155
the data appears in a tabular format.

60
00:03:09,155 --> 00:03:12,410
However, the files are actually in a binary format,

61
00:03:12,410 --> 00:03:15,110
specifically designed for Microsoft Excel.

62
00:03:15,110 --> 00:03:16,955
If you attempt to load them in a text editor,

63
00:03:16,955 --> 00:03:20,550
you will find that the content is not human-readable.

